\f2\b lingzhi mushroom
\f1\b0  is a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polypore"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 polypore}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fungus"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 fungus}} ("bracket fungus") belonging to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genus_(biology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 genus}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ganoderma"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\i \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Ganoderma}}. Its red-varnished, kidney-shaped {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pileus_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 cap}} and peripherally inserted {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stipe_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 stem}} gives it a distinct {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hand_fan"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 fan}}-like appearance. When fresh, the lingzhi is soft, cork-like, and flat. It lacks {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamella_(mycology)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 gills}} on its underside, and instead releases its {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spores"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 spores}} via fine pores. Depending on the age, the pores on its underside may be white or brown.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lingzhi_mushroom#cite_note-Arora-1"}}{\fldrslt 
