Lingzhi mushroom is used in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traditional_Chinese_medicine"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 traditional Chinese medicine}}.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lingzhi_mushroom#cite_note-Cao_2012-2"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [2]}}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lingzhi_mushroom#cite_note-3"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 [3]}} In nature, it grows at the base and stumps of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deciduous_tree"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 deciduous trees}}, especially that of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maple"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 maple}}. Only two or three out of 10,000 such aged trees will have lingzhi growth, and therefore its wild form is extremely rare.
